The ČSSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor the pastry shop.
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will apparently have to overcome the obvious language barriers so that the members of the Prague Board and the City Council understand their renewed SDG colleagues.
The Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new Council of the ČSSD to check their knowledge of the slang marked language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The coded dictionary that used Prague's political flower and cream during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been proven that the new councillors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I really don't know."
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics," said Councillor of Culture Lukáš Kaucký during the "college" terminology examination.
And as far as the veteran politician is concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same.
Maybe they know the concept "golf today."
"Possibly it's the only expression of all the people you asked me that I use from time to time."
"If not, I don't normally use slang."
From the glossary, the definitions of which were published in the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the SDG voting congress, six examples were chosen by the editorial board, in particular those that are particularly related to Prague's municipal authorities.
The socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "largest golf hole in Prague", "go to the pastry shop", "bullnuckle", "traition of the capital" and "blindar".
Three councillors agreed to submit to the test and a quarter, Antonín Weinert, who in the future will be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolinek, refused directly to do so.
"I don't get involved in these things and I don't want to appreciate how civic Democrats have fun."
"What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the implementation of our programs," he said.
As has been seen, alderman Lukáš Kaucký would not have noticed that the previous title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word "Voldemort" does not tell anything; the only term he qualified on the test is "the largest golf hole in Prague".
"It's about the Blanka tunnel," Kaucký says, adding immediately, "But I rather know it from the news."
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course," he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Environment Councillor Lukáš Plachý.
Afterward, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort and Lukš Plachý really is and even knows where to find that character; he also suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; soon Plachý is revealed that it is the headquarters of the companies of Janoušek.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge gained them from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the test participants, there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms among the socio-democrats.
"I asked my colleagues, but it really seems like we don't have anything like that."
"Rather, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations, or we play word games with names," says ČSSD Prague president Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
"At school they called me Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates call me that too," confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The Aktuálně.cz newspaper tested the name and it works.
For his party colleagues, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), Representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they teamed up before the deceitful election during party sponsorship, receives the nickname "Igráček" ("playmobil") from some of his teammates.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz discovered even other nicknames for this Praguen president.
"The doctor of baton rights" apparently recalls that Petr Hulinský obtained his Ph.D. in Law from the Bratislava police academy.
The Government wants to limit the torture of “witches”, as published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are often elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such fate."
"Nor are healthy young women isolated, because they help in the work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of West African state Burkina Faso, takes care of a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information booklet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a catch.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read," warns Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Allegations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, a neighbouring country in Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was caught in the oil used for ritual anointings.
It caught on fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people at all levels of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "Human soul eaters always posed a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease witch hunting, in the Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a large hunt for witches who, supposedly, had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic."
"To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, were forcibly taken randomly chosen men and women from Gambian villages to the president's property in Kanilai," Amnesty International says in its report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
Following international pressure, some 1,000 people were finally released from detention.
Bakala's Tenant: Heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, old and tough, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he was carrying documents with the new three-story leases: his, his daughter's, and his son's, who is serving his sentence.
All three have just been caught in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of CZK 3,500 per month, the child will pay from next year CZK 4,100 for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it has no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
Civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends tenants not to sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes a gesture.
"Everybody says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major test laboratory for liberalisation.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of Ostrava's four and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a bright button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a little piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly gives time to read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues, and similar matters.
Letters with the new leases will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18 a special window is opened at the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," respond, after briefly doubting, the workers who find themselves in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and former mining floors in Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already treated loud and clear by the Vice-President of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my fucking bathroom dish," the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, at the moment they come mostly retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the February rent discount.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," says the window clerk.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on rent, the matter must be settled by an independent judge.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and completely in accordance with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of the employees of RPG Byty and a man in the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so people may wait," he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments, in the four years from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most 7.50 CZK per square meter per month," it is indicated on the screen.
Only increase by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, it is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 kroner per square metre," says RPG.
In 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale from four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent rise (see the chart) back in the flats, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rent-up agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design's employees can come to it.
Architectural projects company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous known buildings of Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow the architects and liners to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of the children.
The mini-guard was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-care centre is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an amount of more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-guard running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the application for funding was submitted by Economy Rating.
The care of children is provided by qualified personnel; moreover, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present for their care throughout the day; the day-care centre currently accommodates children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a "mini-guard", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the day-care centre is flexible in order to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-care programme are comparable to the regular pre-school curriculum.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality teaching: from basic learning to school readiness, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children from school late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally creates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The house cover plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, we observe a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
It snakes and the torsion of the forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 in the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house from the year 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
Architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project were created ornaments for the apartment representative of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudí's Güell Park, where other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic shape, the premises shortly after its completion were nicknamed "the house of bones".
Others, because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, on top of the construction, appears the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating period with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
His forty - five - degree inclination may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the construction standards of the moment and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although clearly in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so impacted with the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of sun.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings into the city.
