How to choose the mattress and the bed: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie down, that is, the mattress and the somier.
First of all, they must be perfectly complemented in order for them to be adapted to specific users.
Numerous elements, including the owner's weight, height, state of health and sex, come into play during the election.
It is also important the type of interior in which the mattress and the somier are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they are "heated" more slowly.
In addition, they often weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them around more frequently.
If the canals in the centre are not properly aerated and above are on a firm basis, they keep the moisture inside. Mold may even appear below.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower and tougher surface.
"Almost all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here."
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"This type of mattress is also recommended for people with diabetes who have long nervous system problems, so they get bad information about joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech Tropico brand."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate the viscoelastic.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
Optimizes your stiffness and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not spin like after a hard match.
He just goes to sleep better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to your height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, it is recommended at least 120 to 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple standard to calculate the width: when lying down face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards your elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, expert from Cechu čalouník
In double rooms, each needs its own mattress and so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the boxes at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interiors a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeter are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When you touch it with your hand or when you settle on the mattress, you should certainly not notice the docks," says Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of spring.
The fully quilted bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you can't wash their holster, which is often done today.
And, since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a life-long guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
Therefore, sellers give advice: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, carefully take care of cleaning and washing the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers are currently made with zip closures throughout their perimeter, so when they are opened they stay in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress may seem like a fight between a fly weight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a somier, do you have a firm board?
Never!
At most for beds designed to spend one night visiting.
However, it should make (if you don't already have them) ventilation holes in the board and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulating sheet bedding containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g. a combination of latex and coconut fiber) may be used, although it is always better to use a bedding box with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar area are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated.
Articulating sheet springs should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows pressing or even tilting the sheets in such a way that they "round" perfectly to the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is something very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "males", began to use a softer area precisely around their shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are soms with cross structure or tablets with the so-called multitorsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and bedding, if you use a bad pillow (large and "soft"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must hold the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that they can relax their muscles.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder spring or softer area of the mattress) as the shoulder height.
Modern mattresses have something to do, apparently, with the original mattresses filled with straw.
Manufacturers continue to increasingly use natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are fashionable.
Oil-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is manufactured, are filled with natural oils, e.g. castor or soy.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soy.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček of Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" with vegetal breeze extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "heat" the sheath.
The red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warmth.
The favorites these days?
Cold foam mattresses, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, make them more permeable than normal polyurethane mattresses and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold and viscoelastic foam allow the manufacture of mattresses from different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have lower VAT, since they are considered to be sanitary means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and bedding.
Sometimes offers from manufacturers or sellers can be approved, which sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory memory foam attached to the cover for 11,990 crowns.
The second is obtained free of charge.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and a high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It initially emerged as material for NASA, because during take-off astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is used not only in mattresses, but also for sanitary devices, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
National manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents use people's tracking devices to control their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, to the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We are all trying to tell us that it is not a matter of spying, but of another means of diminishing the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the tracking device suppliers in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices may be abused, for example if they are put in someone's purse without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In their opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns of the fact that, if the child does not want to carry him, he will simply throw him away.
"Even younger children show great creativity in intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"Before, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In his opinion, it is questionable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child has any electronic device that can reveal his or her location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices spreads, you will also look for them, since their sale will certainly take place with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can be of help.
"The device can be configured to regularly send the position after a certain period."
"If he suffers damage, he will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices are equipped with an inclination meter, so if the person simply slips and remains motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
In his view, such a service could be obtained even with mobile smartphones with navigation, on which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
They can therefore be lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, for that reason tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device."
"Or to identify him after some time, which can make the police buy time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the verification of the position with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough fuses to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but it only lasts two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to ignite explosives.
Last year the Ministry of Defence added 224 kilometers of fuse to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the life span of the fuse is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive fuse from the STV Group, a. s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of fuse saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of fuse a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnics of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives each year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek wanted exemption.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometers of fuse.
This length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if that were the case, the army would have sufficient stocks for more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of fuse, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so they limit even shooting practices for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that we are repeatedly bought such quantities of fuse."
"But it's their decision, and they'll certainly know why they're acting like this."
"For us, the army is a good customer whom, as a company, we try to satisfy," admits the commercial director of STV Group, Jan Děcký.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of fuse also saying that he will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group indicates that the fuse has only a useful life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
Upon completion of their useful life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of fuse, it obtained a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's 244-kilometer order," says spokesman Pejšek of the Ministry of Defence's shopping center.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of police pyrotechnics, which eliminate World War II ammunition or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before the end of its useful life.
It was decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in completing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with which MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years there will be the following problem with the current one: we will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old fuse, which is now being bought "barata".
