Winning the "Employer of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun sell the franchises of his hotel.
The last edition, won the competition "Employer of the Year" the 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
His success story looks like it's taken out of a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
Abroad, he realized that quality accommodation was needed at a good price in Liberec.
With the savings he brought together with seasonal overseas jobs and a bank credit he bought a house that was half ruined composed of five floors.
Considering he was still studying his third year at college, he was really brave.
"At present, the quality-price ratio of the accommodation in our area prompted me to do something about it," says Lukáš Pytloun.
He began renting the first reconstructed floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned was invested back in the building, which gradually turned into a 54-room pension.
Since then, in seven years in business, he managed to gradually open up in Liberec four pensions, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of about 300 in all accommodation categories.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year it opened another one of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov or Tise, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise," said businessman number one last year.
"This sale of hotel opening licenses was greatly helped by winning the 'Employer of the Year' contest," adds Pytloun gratefully.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and in the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, they still congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very nice," he recalls.
Without a doubt, it recommends that everyone want to try some company that participates in the contest.
But he felt that it was not necessary to win, but that participation was already beneficial.
He claims that, so far, he continues to live on contacts and acquaintances that, without the contest, he might not have obtained.
"With some people I met thanks to the contest I have started collaborating regularly."
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in the employees,
in total about seventy.
"I have seen that they show greater loyalty and are proud to participate in something that gained general recognition."
