A Survey that Reveals Ridiculous Standards
The Absurdez survey of the year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already succeeded in eliminating some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was made by more than one third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration requested an extract from the business register, although its officials can obtain it with two movements of the mouse.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the business register when it checks the insured's taxes," said ČSZZ spokesman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the Absurdity survey of the year is to consult the rules and regulations that must be respected by companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is the fourth time that it is part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodářské noviny and it is also beginning to create a hobby among the general public.
While last year's edition counted with the participation of 3,000 voters, this year it almost reached 4,000.
And it is not surprising, since we still have a number of legal obligations that must be respected simply in order to trade.
"Perhaps in the number of papers needed for tax returns we are in the first place worldwide," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
Simplification of business rules has been a stated goal of all governments for years.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, the Czech Republic ranks 74th, eight positions worse than last year.
The Absurdez contest of the year was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated every year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
The proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. Then, the contest organizer chooses seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
Win the absurdity that gets the most votes.
For this year's survey, more than one hundred were presented, in particular 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
Examples were sent by businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for road and motorway maintenance pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year's seventy proposals is published on the competition pages.
The announcement of the competition, which is always held at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended this event.
"Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state continually hinders entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade," said Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not left in the water of drunkenness.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the employer's obligation to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a post to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. communication to the labour office by its foreign workers of working trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the law of the so-called green card.
And the third is the charm.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their office a large mirror, a fridge and two floor scales.
Therefore, this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had removed the obligation to have a refrigerator.
