Families will be required to pay additional costs of several hundred kroner per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to take several hundred kroner a month more out of the portfolio from January than they do now.
The price of electricity rises by 4.6 per cent, gas by about 2 per cent, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10 per cent more for the water supply and many will also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kroner a year more than it is now.
However, the main electricity suppliers reduced prices, as support for renewable energy production, in particular photovoltaic, has increased.
However, gas is moderately expensive, especially at the time when heating is most used and therefore consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are expensive across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, the households of Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 kroner per month for central heating from January, while Liberec families will pay more than an additional 1,000 kroner per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rent of infrastructure.
If the rent does not vary, Praguens will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will increase by 7.4%.
The rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague can increase considerably, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will bring to court those who disagree with the new lease.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 floors, could increase next year to 10%.
Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer in the way, because it slowly works
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes them a long time to get drunk."
"Now fashion is strong alcoholic beverages," says Pravo, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán.
"When they get a bottle from their father from the cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"Vote has the advantage of lightening with juice and not smelling so much," he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"It's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use spirits they picked up at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikan, 13- and 14-year-old drinkers usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It started at the age of 12, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, as well as a mixture with ecstasy," says the department's doctor on this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother was not surprised that his daughter disappeared 48 hours," the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest on the part of parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, dependency cannot be properly referred to.
"Alcohol means a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikan.
According to spokesperson Jurinová, forty drunk children were hospitalized this year at the pediatric clinic in Motol until mid-November.
However, statistics show only those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the travelling medical examination, go home to parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink spirits, there are three seasonal ups and downs for Pelikan: witch's day, New Year's Day and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
"On witch's day I've come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at once," adds Pelikan.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and the nutrients missing from the body.
"These are doing much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and don't hurt at all."
"They are only confused about where they are," Pelikan says, adding that patients often lose their good mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients cost about ten thousand crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when during the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend all summer in a youth job so that you would earn enough to pay yourself that night," Pelikan adds.
Health insurance, in his view, perhaps as a retrogressive measure, which often pays people back for treatment, does not do so for children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in the hands of others in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, by which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa - EADS aircraft is located.
This is the first time such a device has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
For the time being, they were only abroad for training or demonstration flights.
This is the two-seater version L-159T1, which so far used the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-seater.
These are still kept in Aer Vodochody and the broker of the sale, Omnipol company, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peješk of the defense press department indicates that it is not yet known when Vodochody's aircraft will be physically withdrawn.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the aircraft repaired long ago, with no additional investments or contributions from the Ministry."
"The two-seaters L-159T1 exchanged in their current state," he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army does not run out of two-seater aircraft, as in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of SEK 200 million for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 two-seater devices.
One of the new planes was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS promised that the planes would be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve as pilots from NATO countries."
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this context," Pejšek points out.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa plane and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion kroner were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not issue a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management states that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army acquired Aer 72 aircraft and only uses 24 aircraft, so it wants to sell the rest.
Buying Casa planes may have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already denounced the Czech Ministry of Defence to the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by issuing a European tender and not by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at the Prague airport of Kbely in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the ring indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest index to annular are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to the age of 60," said co-author of the Ros Eeles study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger may help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this characteristic is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as indicated by Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and simultaneously 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right-hand indica finger shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
For men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33 per cent; for men with ages below 60 per cent the reduction reached 87 per cent.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "proved completely".
