A arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacterium here on Earth, they say it shows that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"Can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic."
"That makes it very peculiar, although it lacks little to be a truly 'alien' type of life form," commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in Thursday's online edition of the publication Science.
There have long been considered to be six major life-critical elements: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have found that bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, at which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated widespread speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "if it shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus".
"Consequently, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, to put it another way, it puts the biochemical machinery on its back," Anbar explains.
The researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, to which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that there may naturally exist a way of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example had never been found to prove that it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth ages, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
"It does suggest that there might be other ways to generate life, not just the way life was formed on Earth formerly," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
