Interviews, email, and other documents first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, get lucrative work by lobbying, to achieve Hampton's silence and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr Hampton and advocated on behalf of them after they had hired Mr Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign assistant, he was excluded under the law from lobbying for his former employer or Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban", which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
Of the evidence that has been made public, "it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the status stirring door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
