Can civics draw a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, a little civicism has been unleashed in Washington this week.
Is it an omen of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to party fighting in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues that should be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what they all say, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to gain partisan points.
The Wednesday public meeting of the president's deficit commission was equally civilized, despite the remaining political differences among members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Now both sides are in a trial period, surveying each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and deeply rooted to suggest any rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite ends.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, the Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment benefit for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to a continuing bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civics can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012," he said.
The motives have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and overturn the new health law.
These lines of support are already evident in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the reduction of expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult work in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials in the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for commitment.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House Republicans and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama about the budget, taxes, and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would bring about the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a deadlock, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch people's reaction carefully.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partidism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans of Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
