In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the story of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint United Nations/Cambodia court issued the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing former head of the well-known torture centre Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among veterans of Anlong Veng's Khmer Rouge, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among former Khmer Rouge, but they can do nothing," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Centre, an independent organization investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is creating divisions within families."
During the rule of the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
