Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest fighters of the Khmer Rouge fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Khmer Rouge elite officials retained their local administrative positions in exchange for laying down their weapons, the plain soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gained few benefits after the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology".
"They were raised without any concept to do business."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge when she was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting herself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone".
"But now life is difficult because we have to self-supply."
