First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took a constitutional reform out of hand to prevent them from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front line was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully lengthened Greece's rescue decision.
