Sport and law fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly planned by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match contested on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the match (which his team had clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time in taking down faults to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will finish as leader of his group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned with two games the team's coach, José Mourinho, and with different financial amounts the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen in the case reported is because it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and which on past occasions has fined its players for analogous acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud of law; for, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but seem to circumvent their meaning.
The question is what kind of damage they cause to the sporty spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with fair play is to prevent the offending players' team from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that they did not conform to what we normally characterize as a trap or law fraud, because their violation of the rules was not made in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They looked forward to and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders gain from intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the opponent is not put in a disadvantageous position nor is profit obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminateness, since the team can be eliminated at the first of change, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension due to card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not run counter to the sporting spirit, of which it is a part, to make strategic decisions in favour of making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is blurred, on this occasion I believe it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
