Rivers under extreme surveillance
Several watercourses are being closely monitored due to heavy rainfall that has been recorded in several regions of the province since Tuesday.
On Wednesday afternoon a landslide occurred in Shawinigan, Mauricio.
As a preventive measure, two houses have been evacuated.
In the evening, another landslide occurred in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A road went down.
From Tuesday to Wednesday night, several regions recorded heavy rainfall, between 40 and 70 millimeters of rain.
In addition, an additional 20-40 millimetres are expected from now until Thursday night, depending on the region.
Sectors to the north of the river and the Outaouais Valley were most affected.
They could receive up to 100 millimeters of rain.
Since these rainfalls are added to the snow thaw that had already accumulated in certain sectors, there are fears that several rivers will be overflowing.
On Wednesday night, the Quebec Civil Security unit issued alerts for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in Lanaudière.
The rivers of the north, in Saint-Jérôme, in the Laurentides, and of Chêne, in Lotbinière, have already caused floods in the past and are under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region, heavy rainfall has caused some lakes to overflow in Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
In Saint-Calixte, heavy rains have dragged a temporary bridge.
As a preventive measure, 10 residences have been evacuated.
In Outaouais, the overflow of certain lakes has led to the closure of several tracks, in particular in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The civilian security unit remains on alert and closely monitors the situation, as indicated by Annik Bouchard, a security adviser.
The Quebec Flood Forecasting Centre, for its part, broadcast on Wednesday announcements communicating the strong floods of several rivers, in particular the Maskinongé, the Assomption, the Ouareau, the Achigan, the Batiscan and the Loup.
Partially Blame Dupont
Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont has suffered a certain setback to the Canadian Council of Radio Television Standards (CCNR) over controversial statements regarding social assistance and Haitians, as well as their rude language on the radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr. Dupont and his CHOI 98.1 FM team had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained "incorrect information about social assistance, improperly negative representation of Haitians, and rude language that should not be used in broadcasts broadcast during the day."
The Council also indicated that discussions on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two persons who had committed suicide, do not violate broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints regarding comments made on broadcasts broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was issued following a complaint by the Common Front of people receiving social assistance from Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the broadcast were not correct.
The presenters must communicate reliable data and not lead to deception.
In relation to suicide, the present Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most members of the Committee had concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the contested episodes of "Dupont le midi" have dealt with a sensitive issue in an equitable and appropriate manner."
Therefore, any blame has been dropped in this regard.
The last dispute concerned statements made after the earthquake in Haiti.
At that time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had led a media confrontation that had provoked numerous reactions.
The presenter of CHOI stated that he had made no donations to help Haitians because he could not know for sure whether the needy would actually receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes improperly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already completed my three-day suspension up there."
"My file has been clean for a year and a half," the presenter said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the use of rude language.
In any case, the CHOI-FM radio network has collaborated "even more than required".
The consequences shall be minimal for the broadcaster, who shall, inter alia, announce decisions once in the hours of the largest hearing within three days.
