A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by nearly one third of the additional reduction that must be made to stabilize the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of concrete major projects that the UN hopes will be adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided to enlighten humans.
Lighting accounts for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of global car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should still be reduced to stabilize, by 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced even twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above that, they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have expressed reservations about fluorocompact light bulbs, since they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers issue instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not fluocompact light bulbs, but coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity that is wasted with incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save a billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
