Avengerous Hackers and Prompt Spies
The WikiLeaks affair has double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi's sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret records should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little appetite) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I don't know, Libération editor), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the US embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published the previous week.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of States can call on the phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into spy centers.
Anyone watching research films knows that perfectly well, we just seem not to know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, public repetition violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea of anyone being able to consult the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verdiges".
But let us enter the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, he could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer hold its own secrets be endured?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public realm; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to place any reserved information on the web, as it would be like posting it on a street sign.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out whether and when a Head of State has flown and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is science fiction and, therefore, novelism, but I imagine government agents moving discreetly on errands with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then preserved, in a single copy, in locked drawers: ultimately, the Watergate's spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the cableless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph (telephone).
Video tapes (analogs) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow for moving forward or backward from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With the high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was secretly planned in embassies.
At present, it is embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's slump in its financing pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked funding pledges (called fast start or early start) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French chapuzas have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.260 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that their commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major follow-up event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparent operation was a significant result and appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as its reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or the level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, France's total aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while respecting its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider each euro borrowed to be equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain profitable investments (often emission reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At best, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of €420 million by making 91.5% loans (€389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (€36.1 million); see the EU document for your own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes a euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a negative double impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term minutiae in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward with discussions on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the issue of "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
